I wish I would have known about keeping my easy days easy. To me it seemed counterintuitive, how could running slower make me faster? I couldn’t make it make sense. Slowing down is where the magic happens, it allows you to build endurance because you can safely add distance without the stress of speed work. Consider your easy runs the bread and butter of running, a time to hit the pavement and forget about your pace and just enjoy running so you can build endurance. When I started implementing easy days that’s when my paces really started to explode! My race times went from 4:25 marathon to a 3:30, and my half went from 1:57 to a 1:38. 

Keep your easy days easy, and your hard days hard! 

Happy running friends!

Going to start this with potential trigger warning. 

Today was a 90 min endurance run with some intervals thrown in. I walked all of my recoveries so in total I walked 15 minutes of this run. 

This past week was the 20th anniversary of my sexual assault. I haven’t felt like running, my emotions have been HUGE, my left eye has not stopped twitching. The thing with trauma is the mind is so fucking powerful, it has the ability to forget/suppress, remember things differently than how they really happened, etc. you you get my drift. 

For years I suppressed and carried on, it wasn’t until I was contacted in 2018 and then went to court in 2021 to testify against my perpetrator that everything re-surfaced and that was one of the hardest weeks of my life, I would rather slide down a razor blade in to a glass of rubbing alcohol before EVER having to go through that week again.. and then the weeks that followed. 

Today on my run the assault was heavy on my mind, it took will-power to get out the door but I am so damn glad that I CHOSE to show up for myself. I allowed myself to process the thoughts that I needed to, FEEL what I needed to feel, and pounded it out on the pavement, when I finished my last interval I bawled like a baby, it was as if everything I have been keeping pinned up finally released, and I think that is what I needed. 

Im not telling you all of this because I want to hear “you’re so strong” or “I’m sorry” I’m not telling you all of this because I want you to feel bad for me. I am telling you this because things like this, things that happened to me, are happening more often than most realize. Be an advocate, speak up if something seems wrong, it is better to over react than to not react at all. 

Also, be kind, IG is a constant highlight reel and I love cheering on everyone but I also think it is important to highlight real life shit because majority is most of us are dealing with things we don’t speak of. Love you all 🫶🏻

Pretty much my problem solving go to 🤣.

If you were to ask me what the 3 biggest changes I made to go from a 4:25 to a 3:30 marathon were, these would be it!! 

First off get a coach! 

⭐️slowdown. Chances are your easy runs are probably not easy enough. 

⭐️ strength train! Strength training prevents injury, it is so important, don’t over complicate it, shoot for 2 days a week. 

⭐️ eating. I struggled with body image and weight for most of my life. You can’t be in a calorie deficit and expect to have amazing race times, the 2 do not go together. 

Happy running, love ya guys!

First marathon in 2020 I thought all of my easy runs needed to be between 9-10 minutes for me to feel like a real runner, I can’t be the only person who use to believe that in order to be a “good” runner I needed to keep my pace under 10 minutes by doing that I always drained when it was time to do speed work. That first marathon took me 4:25:27 to complete. I said I would never run another one. 

Fast forward to 2021 I really buckled down and started listening to my coach and take my easy runs easy and started gaining confidence in my speed work because for once I was finally able to hit certain paces. That year came back and ran a 3:35:32, I missed a BQ by 33 seconds 🤣🤣. 

6 months later I decided to give it one more try and slowed my easy pace even more (10-12 min pace) and really tried to listen to my body. By slowing down I was able to really hit my workouts , I took extra rest days when needed and ran a 3:30 with a 5 minute BQ buffer. 

Sometimes less is more, by slowing down you are still building that aerobic base, can safely increase mileage, allows your body to build strength without too much stress, and increases your body’s ability to transfer and use oxygen, leaving you ready to go on days that are meant for speed work! 80% hard, 20% easy.

Everything always comes full circle.. sometimes 18 years… at the end of it all I had the last word. In the end he plead guilty to sexual assault of a minor and indecency with a child and was sentenced to 15 years in prison.

December 2nd 2021 my perpetrator plead guilty to sexually assaulting  me when I was 15 years old and indecency with a minor, this was after he was found guilty by jury for another case that I testified in. It took 15 years before my case would be brought to light and 18 years before I would see justice. I have seen the ugliest sides of humanity, I have had horrible things done to me by the hands of someone I trusted with my life. I was victim shamed for years, because somehow a young girl in loose fitting scrubs with green frogs is sexually appealing, and therefore was my fault. 
My world at 15 was turned completely upside down. It wasn’t until I went to court (2021) that I realized how much unresolved trauma I still have/had. I hit rock bottom after court, I went to an extremely dark place, my mind just could not shut off, it was all I thought about for weeks. 
Its easy to get lost in my feelings when I talk or think about that day in 2003 and that week of court in 2021. I share my story to raise awareness, to urge others that if you see or hear something that doesn’t seem right, report it. 

Here are some statistics from rainn.org 
•Every 68 seconds an American is sexually assaulted.

•1 out of every 6 women has been the victim of an attempted or completed rape in their life time. 

•About 3% of men (1 in 33) have experienced an attempted or completed rape in their lifetime. 

•66% child victims are between the ages of 12-17 while 34% are under the age of 12. 

On December 2nd, I will be running 20 miles for the 20 years  it took to get justice, I will be running for those who never made it home, for those who were just babies when their innocence was stolen, for those who have not able to share their story, and for those that have also brought their story to light!

Please feel free to join me, even if only for a mile. If you are local message me and I will tell you time and place, if you want to join from afar please run and tag me in your story! We are stronger together ❤️.

Finally getting around to writing my recap of the White River Marathon! To date this is the smallest marathon I have ever ran, it takes place in a cute little town called Cotter and was easy to navigate. I was pleasantly surprised when I realized our Airbnb was not even half a mile from the starting line, talk about convenience. 

Packet pickup takes place at the school and the night before they host a pasta dinner. With it being a small race there was no weaving in and out of people at the start line, plenty of room for everyone, they had aid stations every 2 miles, and my watch was spot on with the mile markers ( I love when that happens)! The first part was foggy and kind of sleepy hollow eerie. 

Cons, mentally this was one of the hardest races I have ran, it was like being on a solo run at marathon pace, I had a hard time staying engaged and focused, I kept fidgeting around with my phone and watch. At mile 17 my phone flew out of my flip belt and I had to back track to get it. Around mile 24 the route went from pavement to a trail and I’m still not sure how I felt about that lol. 

I missed a BQ by less than a minute and I thought it would sting but honestly it didn’t. Considering how my training cycle went I was thrilled with my time, I was expecting to come in around 3:40. I would love to go back and run this again now that I am familiar with the course, and spend a couple extra days there to explore.

Recipe  For the Dough:

For the Filling
• 4 Tbsp melted butter
• 1⅓ cup brown sugar
• 2 Tbsp cinnamon

For the Icing:
• 1 tsp milk
• 1½ cups confectioners sugar
• 4 Tbsp softened butter
• 1 tsp vanilla extract

Combine dough ingredients to your bread machine in the order listed, turn on dough cycle, and let it work its magic.

When Nathan and I first started dating and staying overnight with each other he would make me coffee in the morning.. I always thought it was the sweetest gesture. 

Believe it or not he use to wake up earlier than me but when I started marathon training getting up before everyone else was the only way to make training consistently work. On mornings I don’t run he always brings me coffee in bed.  l posted on my stories once about him bringing coffee to me and a guy messaged wanting to know what I do for him and said “just wait until you have been together for years and he stops”… well here we are 4 years (going on 5) later and I can’t tell you how many cups of coffee the man has brought me. 

It’s a daily act of kindness, he literally is filling my love cup before I am even out of bed, such a simple act reminds that I am important, and valued. I don’t know about other households but in ours we both work long hours, I am a stay at home WORKING mom who works a minimum of 52 hours a week. Waking up to that cup of coffee by the bed is his way of saying I love you, I appreciate you, and I hope you have a great day. 

By him keeping my cup full it allows me to pour in to other areas of our life, family, and work because I dont have to fixate on filling my own cup. So here is my Ted talk of the day on filling love cups and a reminder that the small things really do matter more than most know. That’s all, happy whatever day of the week it is ♥️.
